><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">This week, in what may be remembered as another pivotal regr=
ession in Major
League Baseball=E2=80=99s retreat from the zeitgeist, ESPN chairman <strong=
>Jimmy Pitaro </strong>told the league that his network would be opting out=
 of its annual $570 million contract at the end of this season. Before ESPN=
=E2=80=99s letter could even be FedExed to MLB headquarters in Midtown, com=
missioner <strong>Rob Manfred </strong>was trying to get ahead of the news =
and put his own spin on the ball. =E2=80=9CWe do not think it=E2=80=99s ben=
eficial for us to accept a smaller deal to remain on a shrinking
platform,=E2=80=9D Manfred wrote in a memo to his owners that soon somehow =
made its way into the digital pages of The Athletic=E2=80=94thereby likely =
putting the final kiss-off on a relationship that has existed for three and=
 a half decades.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Manfred, a former labor lawyer who has=
 been navigating the balkanized sports media landscape, wasn=E2=80=99t quit=
e done. In the extraordinarily chummy and relationships-based world of spor=
ts
media, he seemed intent on delivering the message that his league didn=E2=
=80=99t need Disney=E2=80=99s money and that, despite the cratering of the =
regional sports network industry, he had plenty of options. =E2=80=9CGiven =
that MLB provides strong viewership, valuable demographics, and the exclusi=
ve right to cover unique events like the Home Run Derby, ESPN=E2=80=99s dem=
and to reduce rights fees is simply unacceptable. As a result, we have mutu=
ally agreed to terminate our agreement,=E2=80=9D the league said in a state=
ment.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This framing was a source of <em>great</em=
> amusement for executives at both ESPN and rival media organizations=E2=80=
=94including current and possible future league partners=E2=80=94all of who=
m knew that it wasn=E2=80=99t quite so <em>mutual</em>. The seeds of the ML=
B-ESPN contretemps will be familiar to the readership of my partner <strong=
>John Ourand</strong>, who has been reporting on all this dialectic for <em=
>years</em>, but if
not, a quick refresher=E2=80=A6 Baseball, a game popularized by radio and m=
onetized through its tonnage, has been losing some of its media cachet for =
years amid the growth of the NFL, increase in televised college sports, asc=
ent of the NBA, and proliferation of niche sports. To wit: A decade-plus ag=
o, Manfred and Pitaro negotiated a $750 million a year, eight-year package =
that ran through 2021. In 2021, of course, they re-upped into the current $=
570 million per annum deal. (Yes, it=E2=80=99s $570 million, not
$550 million).=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But then Manfred went and reset th=
e market by striking substantially cheaper add-on deals, like licensing a p=
ackage of Friday night games to Apple TV+ for $85 million, in 2022, and Sun=
day morning games to Roku for $10 million, in 2024. These may have been del=
ightful incremental revenue plays, but they backfired. As The Athletic=E2=
=80=99s <strong>Andrew Marchand </strong>noted, the Roku deal is
only netting each team $300,000, =E2=80=9Cwhich is less than half the minim=
um rookie salary of $760,000 for one player.=E2=80=9D More importantly, mea=
sured against those deals, ESPN=E2=80=99s package=E2=80=94which includes <e=
m>Sunday Night Baseball</em>, the wild card playoffs, and the Home Run Derb=
y=E2=80=94seemed overpriced.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">ESPN prides itself on it=
s fiscal responsibility, and has a sophisticated internal pricing model to =
gauge the estimated
R.O.I. on live rights investments. (As do Amazon and Netflix and others=E2=
=80=A6) Obviously, you can=E2=80=99t anticipate which teams will be hot dur=
ing the course of an eight-year deal, or whether <strong>Shohei</strong> wi=
ll suffer an injury, but there=E2=80=99s a lot they <em>can </em>anticipate=
 about viewership totals and sell-through rates. As CNBC=E2=80=99s <strong>=
Alex Sherman </strong>noted on Ourand=E2=80=99s excellent podcast, <em>The =
Varsity</em>, ESPN ostensibly gets a higher R.O.I. from newfangled leagues,=
 like TGL, than
a banner product such as <em>Sunday Night Baseball</em>.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;"><br/>In any case, they never actually ran the numbers on thi=
s because Manfred made it clear from the outset that he wasn=E2=80=99t will=
ing to entertain any offer below the existing rate. But, having surveyed se=
veral media executives with a vested interest in that answer, it seems like=
ly the true value is probably a little more than <em>half</em> of what ESPN=
 is currently paying=E2=80=94yes, the MLB deal was worth a pair of NFL
playoff or Christmas Day games. And, of course, any new deal would need to =
include the sorts of local packages that provide the tonnage that matters m=
ost on streaming.</p></div>
